Improvements in fisheries management are most effective if they are informed by the main drivers of fishing (e.g., commerce, recreation, subsistence, culture). To accomplish this, we obtained information on fish flow across the MHI. This information included the distribution of catch, and whether it was: (1) kept for home consumption; (2) given away; (3) sold (or bartered); (4) released; (5) used as bait and/or (6); used for other purposes (
  Hardt, 2011; 
  Kittinger, 2013; 
  Kittinger et al., 2015). Fish flow information estimates how catch from nearshore marine ecosystems is used by local fishers and the role it has in local economies and households (
  Glazier & Kittinger, 2012; 
  Kittinger, 2013).
